snippet.textDisplay:
AMD has highlighted the main reason as to why they don't plan on adding support for Zen 3 Ryzen CPUs on pre-500-series chipsets to be the flash memory limitation. As per AMD, the flash memory chips that store the BIOS have capacity limitations, and not all AM4 boards feature dual-BIOS chip design (usually found on more expensive and high-end boards).

I would have to say I'm pretty disappointed in AMD if the only issue is that some motherboards have to small bios flash chips we have enough E waste already I'm sure they could support motherboards by removing old Zen one CPUs from the microcode to make room for the new zen 3 cpus maybe I'll get lucky and the bios mod community will figure out how to make Zen 3 work

I know my board has a 128 mb bios flash chip I'm pretty sure there's enough room for the new microcode on my board and I think people should be pushing AMD do the right thing and support older motherboards B450 X470 and possibly X370 and B350

My brother has a ga-ab350m-ds3h and due to the bios size they removed support for Bristol Ridge AMD 7th Gen A-series/ Athlonâ„¢ X4 series APU's
they then had room to add support for the new zen 2 CPUs

I honestly think if the bios size limitation is the only problem with using older motherboards people need to push for support for them

I honestly just stopped using my core 2 quad 9400 @3.5ghz at the start of this year had it for around 10 years
my upgrade to the Ryzen 2600X was one heck of an upgrade but I am disapointed my 5 month old ASUS ROG STRIX B450-F
will not work with the new zen 3 :(  guess I should have gotten a x570 motherboard

snippet.textDisplay:
The problem isn't that they dropped support for b450 x470, the problem is a lot of us buying Ryzen 5 3600(or below) range of processors didn't want to spend a lot of money on the motherboard, so x570 was not our option, especially in countries like India where the prices are insane, and then they never released b550 for so long that most of us trying to save a buck ended up with 400 series motherboards because Ryzen 5 really doesn't require a fancy x570 motherboard and it was only logical to save equivalent of about $100 for people like me in countries with inflated prices.
I think support will end up coming to 400 series boards with good VRMs anyways otherwise used market will be the way to go for future cpu upgrades.
I think there isn't much reason to panic then, but I feel it really was a clever move from AMD to delay b550 for so long and might have been a market tactic to ensure future sale of future motherboards, which is fine I guess, still better than how Intel treats generations.
Moreover, if you're someone with a 3600(or X) or anything below with a good 400 series board, you're set. Even if they don't end up bringing 4000 series support to them, you still have the option for high end 3000 series CPUs when getting hands on them will be much cheaper and looking at the trend of older Ryzen chips, it probably will be.
